Apple on Saturday introduced new RED-colouRED iPhone 7 and 7 Plus as its(RED) Special Edition iPhone in South Africa.iStore said the special edition was on the shelves since April 8. The iPhone 7 and iPhone 7 Plus (RED) comes in a vibrant RED aluminium finish, in recognition of more than 10 years of partnership between Apple and (RED), iStore said.iStore said by purchasing this product, customers could contribute to the global fund and bring the world a step closer to an Aids-free generation. For each phone sold, Apple will donate an unspecified amount to the (RED) Global Fund.Thde iPhone 7 and iPhone 7 Plus, which launched on October, 14, 2016, are the best, most advanced iPhones so far. Featuring an all-new advanced camera system, dust and water resistant design, stereo speaker system and the A10 fusion chip which is the most powerful chip on any smartphone while delivering the best battery life ever in an iPhone.Both phones are powered by iOS 10, the biggest release of the world s most advanced mobile operating system. Since we began working with (RED) 10 years ago, our customers have made a significant impact in fighting the spread of Aids through the purchase of our products, from the original iPod nano(RED) Special Edition all the way to today s lineup of Beats products and accessories for iPhone, iPad and Apple Watch, Tim Cook, Apple s CEO said. The introduction of this special edition iPhone in a gorgeous red finish is our biggest (RED) offering to date in celebration of our partnership with (RED) and we can t wait to get it into customers hands. Apple is the world s largest corporate donor to the global fund, contributing more than $130m (R1.8bn) as part of its partnership with (RED), Deborah Dugan, (RED) CEO said. Combining the global reach of the world s most loved smartphone with our efforts to provide access to lifesaving ARV medication in sub-Saharan Africa, customers now have a remarkable opportunity to make a difference and contribute to the global fund. (RED) s critical work provides access to life-saving HIV-Aids programmes in sub-Saharan Africa, which is hometo more than two thirds of the world s HIV-positive population.INDIE BOYCE